To model the booking cancellation prediction task, a wide and deep neural network architecture was implemented using Keras. This approach combines the strengths of both memorization and generalization:

The wide component uses cross-product features to memorize frequent feature interactions
The deep component is a feedforward neural network that captures nonlinear relationships and generalizes to unseen patterns

To evaluate the effectiveness of this architecture, three different wide and deep models were constructed, each varying in the depth of the deep branch:

Model 1 (Shallow): A single hidden layer
Model 2 (Moderate depth): Two hidden layers
Model 3 (Deeper network): Three hidden layers

All models share the same wide input but differ in their capacity to learn hierarchical feature representations in the deep component.

Each model was trained using the same training data and evaluated on a validation set during training. The training and validation performance were tracked across epochs using the history object returned by the Keras fit() function.

To visualize learning behavior and detect overfitting, training and validation loss curves were plotted for each model. These plots provide insight into:

Whether the model is underfitting (both losses high)
Whether the model is overfitting (training loss decreases while validation loss increases)
How quickly each model converges

By comparing these curves across models, it is possible to observe how increasing network depth affects learning dynamics and stability.

This experimental setup allows for a systematic comparison of model complexity and its impact on performance, forming the basis for selecting the most effective architecture.
